## Part 2: Commercial & Academic Tools in Production

### Who is Selling This Right Now?

| Tool | Company | Approach | Price | Limitation |
|------|---------|----------|-------|------------|
| **Derek Nexus** | Lhasa Ltd | Rule-based expert system | $$$$ (enterprise) | No probabilistic output, brittle rules |
| **ADMET Predictor** | Simulations Plus | QSAR + ML hybrid | $$$ | Black-box, no atom-level explanation |
| **Schrödinger ADME** | Schrödinger Inc | Physics + ML | $$$$$ | Requires full Schrödinger suite |
| **pkCSM** | University of Melbourne | Web QSAR | Free/academic | No multi-label, single property at a time |
| **SwissADME** | SIB | Descriptor-based | Free | No toxicity, only ADME properties |
| **Chemprop** | MIT Coley Lab | D-MPNN GNN | Open source | No UI, command-line only |
| **DeepTox** | BIML Innsbruck | Deep Ensemble | Academic | Not maintained since 2016 |

### What They All Have in Common (Their Gaps)

```
❌ Most are black boxes — no explanation of WHY a molecule is toxic
❌ Commercial tools cost $10,000–$100,000/year — inaccessible  
❌ No atom-level visualization — chemists can't act on the output
❌ No live SMILES input + instant result — batch processing only
❌ Not open-source — can't be audited or reproduced
❌ Trained on proprietary data — no reproducibility
```

